 Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1110–":"about 1110–Deceased","1110–Female":"1110–Deceased","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1130–Male":"1130–Deceased","1145–Male":"1145–Deceased","1148–Male":"1148–Deceased","1090–Male":"1090–Deceased","1090–Female":"1090–Deceased","1090":"1090","1148":"1148","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","about 1148":"about 1148","about 1145":"about 1145","1130":"1130","about 1110":"about 1110","about 1130":"about 1130","about 1120":"about 1120","about 1131":"about 1131","Crickhowell, Breconshire, Wales":"Crickhowell, Breconshire, Wales","Brecon, Breconshire, Wales":"Brecon, Breconshire, Wales","Brecknock, Breconshire, Wales":"Brecknock, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Of,,Glamorgan,Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Talgarth, Breconshire, Wales":"Talgarth, Breconshire, Wales","Caerleon, Gwent, Wales":"Caerleon, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Janet","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a diminutive of   Jane  , already in common use in the Middle English period. It remained in use in Scotland and in some parts of England well into the 17th century and was revived at the end of the 19th century to much more widespread use, while still retaining its popularity in Scotland. Since the 1960s, however, it has rather gone out of fashion in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Jannet","meanings":["Originally a diminutive of   Jane  , already in common use in the Middle English period. It remained in use in Scotland and in some parts of England well into the 17th century and was revived at the end of the 19th century to much more widespread use, while still retaining its popularity in Scotland. Since the 1960s, however, it has rather gone out of fashion in Britain."]}]},{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."],"variants":[{"name":"Hywell","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."]},{"name":"Howell","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Brecon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Normand, Renald, Adelard, Alphonse, Armand, Gaetan, Laurent, Serge, Adrien, Aime.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and English (of Norman origin): ethnic name for a Breton, from Old French <i>breton</i>, oblique case of <i>bret</i> (see   Bret  ). Compare   Lebreton  , see also English   Brett  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Jean Élie/Hélie <i>dit</i> (Le) Breton from Ménéac in Morbihan, Brittany (France), who married Jeanne Labbé in Sainte-Famille, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1669. His descendants also bear the surname   Elie  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bret","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which originated in the Middle Ages as an ethnic name for one of the Bretons who arrived in England in the wake of the Norman Conquest. As a surname it is most common in East Anglia, where Breton settlement was particularly concentrated. As a given name, it enjoyed something of a vogue in the 1970s and has since remained modestly popular, especially in the United States."]},{"name":"Brittain","meanings":["Irish: Brith, painted, speckled, and tain, country, meaning the country of the painted inhabitants"]},{"name":"Britton","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Breton  , and ethnic name for a Breton, from Old French <i>Breton</i>, the oblique case form of Old French <i>Bret</i>; compare   Brittain   and   Brett  ."]},{"name":"Bretton","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from a place near Exminster in Devon, called in Old English <i>Brӯningtūn</i> ‘settlement associated with <i>Brӯni</i>’. The latter is a personal name derived from <i>bryne</i> ‘fire, flame’. The modern given name may also be a variant of   Branton ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Janet verch Hywel of Brecon was born about 1110, in Brecon, Breconshire, Wales, her father, Hywel ap Llywelyn, was 22 and her mother, Marsli Gunter, was 22. She married Genillin ap Rhys \"Gôch\" about 1131, in Crickhowell, Breconshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"about 1110–":"umbes 1110–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1148–Male":"1148–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1090":"1090","1148":"1148","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","about 1148":"umbes 1148","about 1145":"umbes 1145","1130":"1130","about 1110":"umbes 1110","about 1130":"umbes 1130","about 1120":"umbes 1120","about 1131":"umbes 1131","Crickhowell, Breconshire, Wales":"Crickhowell, Brec